---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import CaseHero from '../../components/CaseHero.astro';
import CasePrevNext from '../../components/CasePrevNext.astro';
import CTABanner from '../../components/CTABanner.astro';
import Footer from '../../components/Footer.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="Walt Disney World Public Affairs" description="77% bounce rate. A research-led redesign that cut exits by 44% and made Disney's community impact finally visible." ogImage="/images/disney_hero.webp" ogType="article">
  <CaseHero logo="/images/disney_logo.webp" logoAlt="Walt Disney World" title="Walt Disney World Public Affairs Digital Transformation" category="Research-Led UX & Information Architecture" meta={[{label:'Client',value:'Walt Disney World Public Affairs'},{label:'Role',value:'Senior UX Strategist — research, IA, and interface design'},{label:'Agency',value:'Voce Communications / Porter Novelli'},{label:'Technology',value:'Sketch, Adobe Creative Suite, Google Analytics, heatmap testing'}]} heroImage="/images/disney_hero.webp" heroAlt="Walt Disney World Public Affairs — digital platform redesign" />
  <div class="case-body">
    <section class="case-section">
      <h2 class="case-h2">The Problem</h2>
      <p>The site had poor visibility for community organizations — 43% of engaged traffic — seeking donations through a 5+ step process buried in navigation. Press releases were undifferentiated in a single feed, causing journalist abandonment. A 77% category-page bounce rate confirmed usability failures that analytics alone couldn't explain.</p>
    </section>
    <div class="case-full-img"><img src="/images/disney01.webp" alt="Disney Public Affairs — site audit findings" loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1620" height="860" /></div>
    <section class="case-section">
      <h2 class="case-h2">Research & Discovery</h2>
      <p>Competitive audit across 12 Fortune 500 Public Affairs sites and theme park properties. Heatmap analysis identified navigation invisibility issues. Moderated sessions with 8 participants showed users couldn't distinguish Public Affairs content from the main resort site — a fundamental positioning failure that no amount of copy optimization could fix.</p>
    </section>
    <div class="case-grid-2">
      <img src="/images/disney02.webp" alt="Disney — heatmap analysis" loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="760" height="520" />
      <img src="/images/disney03-1.webp" alt="Disney — user research sessions" loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="760" height="520" />
    </div>
    <section class="case-section">
      <h2 class="case-h2">Information Architecture</h2>
      <p>Restructured hierarchy for three distinct user journeys: media professionals, community organizations, and general stakeholders. Each audience received a dedicated entry point with content organized around their specific tasks rather than Disney's internal communication structure.</p>
    </section>
    <div class="case-full-img"><img src="/images/disney04.webp" alt="Disney — information architecture redesign" loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1620" height="860" /></div>
    <section class="case-section">
      <h2 class="case-h2">Wireframes & Flow Optimization</h2>
      <p>Donation flow reduced from 5+ steps to 2 interactions with 5/5 task success in testing. Press content separated into categorized feeds by topic and audience type, eliminating the single undifferentiated stream. Navigation language replaced internal Disney terminology with user-facing task descriptions.</p>
    </section>
    <div class="case-grid-2">
      <img src="/images/disney05-1.webp" alt="Disney — wireframe flows" loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="760" height="520" />
      <img src="/images/disney06.webp" alt="Disney — donation flow redesign" loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="760" height="520" />
    </div>
    <section class="case-section">
      <h2 class="case-h2">Visual Design & Responsive Implementation</h2>
      <p>Visual design established clear distinction between Disney Public Affairs and the main resort brand while maintaining the organizational credibility required for media and community audiences. Fully responsive implementation across all breakpoints, replacing a desktop-only experience that had failed mobile visitors entirely.</p>
    </section>
    <div class="case-full-img"><img src="/images/disney07.webp" alt="Disney Public Affairs — final responsive design" loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1620" height="860" /></div>
    <section class="case-section case-section--results">
      <h2 class="case-h2">Results & Impact</h2>
      <ul class="case-results">
        <li><strong>Exit rate:</strong> 44% decrease site-wide</li>
        <li><strong>Bounce rate:</strong> 24% decrease across category pages</li>
        <li><strong>Session duration:</strong> 26% increase</li>
        <li><strong>Donation flow:</strong> Reduced from 5+ steps to 2 interactions</li>
        <li><strong>Mobile usability:</strong> Rebuilt to fully operational across all breakpoints</li>
      </ul>
    </section>
  </div>
  <CasePrevNext currentSlug="walt-disney-world" />
  <CTABanner />
  <Footer />
</BaseLayout>
